<br>
For a long time I was oblivious to the presence of guilds, then for a longer time yet, to their pervasiveness and importance.  Heck I had really never paid attention to the term &quot;uber&quot; until recently and until 2.5 weeks ago I had never seen the term HOSS.  Several weeks ago a dear friend of mine, with whom I have played EQ almost from my start back in May, and I decided to investigate, and ultimately join, a guild.  Since then we have been looking, and in some cases, going on raids with guilds that we were interested in, or that had indicated an interest in us.  In many cases these were guild of people who we had met and enjoyed in game.  It has beena fascinating odyssey that is not yet over.<br>
<br>
Reading though about post 50 level gaming a couple of things have become clear:  You CAN make level 60, albeit slowly, by not being guilded, and that you probably CANNOT obtain the gear that makes possible some activity without being guilded, or having a group of people of guild like level and resources.  And it is pretty clear from game design and some of the things Sony is directly quoted as saying that the design does in fact require guilding or extreme high level cooperation.  <br>
<br>
In the Uber Quest to decide what guild is best to join we have discovered a lot of things....  there are guilds that have earned themselves some pretty despicable reputations...hearing that from one person can be disgruntlement, 2 or 3 related people can be sour grapes, but multiple unrelated people and it becomes a pretty clear pattern with a high liklihood of containing substantial trurth.  As a result there some guilds I will not consider.<br>
<br>
One of the things that had always bothered me about the guilded, was grouping with them and sometimes in the midst of great danger being told &quot;Guildie calling, gotta go&quot; and having them disband and leave with no time to replace them or head to safety.  My friend and I decided early on we would never join a guild that condoned this, let alone encouraged or required.  For the most part I now believe that much of that was excuses offered for bad behaviour by immature players.  That is not to say I don't understand leaving for a genuine emergency as long as your leaving does not create and leave behind yet another emergency.<br>
<br>
Leaving other playes in your group at risk seldom can be justified.  Sometimes it can be an oversight but a pattern indicates selfish or immature behaviour.  Nothing illegal, but wrong from an interaction basis and likely to get one placed on my &quot;no group&quot; list if not my &quot;no rez&quot; list.  By the same token there are people who will do all they can to help group members and others suceed without risking others.  There are guilds like that too...they both go to the top of my list.<br>
<br>
I was online during the &quot;sleeper&quot; raid the other night and saw all of the rumours, flames, observations, comments, huzzahs and complaints.  I was told definitevly that the sleeper was awakened...  I was also told definitevly that it wasn't as the 4th warder was not killed.  I still do not know which is truth, not the consequences except speculation I have picked up as sites.<br>
<br>
The lawyer in me can find all sorts of &quot;holes&quot; in the EULA and the rules of behaviour and the sprite in me wants ot exploit every one, and I may.  BUT, if in fact Sony/Verant created a once per server &quot;sleeper&quot; encounter then they must have anticipated that someday some group would do that encounter, as apparently has happened on other servers.  And if they didn't want the dragon killable, they would make in UNKILLABLE... instead of having a billion HP or whatever.  Ditto the warders.  <br>
<br>
Yes it may well be unnice or unsportsmanlike to kill something that ends the potential enjoyment of many other people on the server..... and yes FFAing raids instead of coordinating may adversely affect the enjoyment of others who are members of coorperating guilds and point up the non-cooperators as being Adam Henrys (as we used to call them in law enforcement.)  But it isn't illegal....yet.<br>
<br>
This kind of behaviour has svereal consequences besides the visceral satisfaction of &quot;having done it&quot;.  1.) It can cause prospective &quot;good citizen&quot; guild members to go elsewhere to more well behaved guilds; 2.) It can cause creative legalists (like me) to find all sorts of devious, nasty, but also entirely legal ways to express displeasure at the arrogance; 3.) Eventually it can cause Sony/Verant to change the rules and limit our in game freedom.  Scuba diving for example is essentially a self-regulated activity here in the US and it will likely stay that way until and unless someone continually abusses the privilege, then the government will move in and regulate.  And Sony, just like any other consumer corporation, does listen to its customer base (Look at the change in the Cleric Epic recently.)  There are a LOT more $9.95/mo on this server that are NOT in Uber guilds than there are in.  So the actions of a guild exercising its freedom to do so, may result in a loss of that freedom for them and all others, by rules change or change of game design.<br>
<br>
All of these things I have seen and heard and whatever happens form here on will have an impact on my decision as to where to go, what to do and whom to join.<br>
<br>
<br>
Arundeltempletn<br>
Vicar of Tunare<br>
51st Season (and holding)<br>
<br>
-Robin Hood:Swords of Waylon- &quot;Nothing is forgotten, nothing is EVER forgotten.&quot;<br>
